<DOC><DOCNO> AP881107-0181 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0743EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-07 0510</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0533</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An investor group led by the buyout firmForstmann Little andamp; Co. and that includes the consumer products giantProcter andamp; Gamble Co. emerged as a possible ``white knight'' in thefight for RJR Nabisco Inc.   Forstmann Little said late Friday the group was considering a bidfor the food and tobacco products company that would surpass a $20.7billion offer made by Nabisco management and a competing $20.3billion bid by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc.   In a statement, Forstmann Little said a special committee of theRJR Nabisco board set up to review the offers ``had welcomed theinterest'' of the group, which also included the food companiesRalston Purina Co. and Castle andamp; Cooke Inc. and the investment firmGoldman, Sachs andamp; Co.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Universities and research centers have turned computers back onafter sweeping out a ``virus'' epidemic that infected machinesacross the country.   Specialists said Friday the virus proved to be a nuisance andslowed computers but apparently caused no damage.   The virus is a sort of rogue program that reproduced in computersand apparently instructed them to send copies of itself to othermachines through a research network, ARPANET.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC said it plans tosell its British commercial printing business and is consideringselling other assets following its takeover of the U.S.-basedpublishing and information services concern Macmillan Inc.   The company, which is headed by Robert Maxwell, said the movesare part of a restructuring that will enable it to focus more onpublishing and less on printing following the Macmillan deal.   Maxwell was also elected Friday to replace Edward P. Evans, whoresigned as Macmillan's chairman.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Poland's national airline said it will acquireits first non-Soviet aircraft, three Boeing 767 widebody jets, in adeal that will make Boeing Co. the first supplier of modern, Westernjets to a Soviet bloc nation.   The deal announced Friday is worth $220 million to Boeing andGeneral Electric Co., the engine supplier.</TEXT><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chubb Corp. has offered another $43.7 millionin coverage to some farmers whose applications it had rejected thisyear.   Chubb's offer comes as the insurer faces a class-action lawsuitby farmers in 10 states who say they were unfairly denied droughtinsurance.   The company said Friday it is willing to proceed to reach asettlement with farmers who applied for drought insurance, but wererejected and filed suit against Chubb.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal regulators have announced that afinancially troubled New Jersey savings and loan institution wasbeing acquired by a California institution.   Officials said Friday the acquisition of Lincoln Federal Savingsand Loan Association of Westfield, N.J. represented the 140thtroubled Sandamp;L case resolved this year. Lincoln Federal is beingacquired by First Nationwide Bank of San Francisco.   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. said it wasproviding $145.7 million in assistance as part of the deal.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>